{{Infobox person | name = Elon A. Ganor | image = אילון גנור 2.jpg | birth_date = 1950 | birth_place = Geneva, Switzerland | residence = Israel | occupation = Entrepreneur, artist }}
'''Elon A. Ganor''' ({{lang-he|אילון גנור}}; born 1950) is an Israeli entrepreneur and artist known mainly for his role as one of the world's first [[VoIP]] pioneers. He served as Chairman and CEO of [[VocalTec]] Ltd (Nasdaq CALL), the company behind the creation of “Internet Phone”, the world's first commercial software product that enabled voice communication over the internet, known initially as “Internet Telephony” and later as VoIP.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.tmcnet.com/blog/tom-keating/docs/cti-buyers-guide-1996.pdf|publisher=Computer Telephony Interaction Magazine|title=Internet Phone Release 4|last=Keating|first=Tom|accessdate=November 7, 2007|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilocus.com/2007/07/the_10_that_established_voip_p_2.html|publisher=iLocus|title=The 10 that Established VOIP (Part 1: VocalTec)|accessdate=January 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name="cnn"/><ref>{{cite news| last= Brown| first = Erin| date = July 8, 1996| title= VocalTec Software For Internet Phone Calls| url = http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1996/07/08/214359/index.htm| website = http://money.cnn.com/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| date =March 19, 1996| title=Internet Phone from VocalTec| url = http://www.speech.cs.cmu.edu/comp.speech/Section1/Phone/vocaltec.html | website = http://www.cmu.edu/index.shtml}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| date = Nov 8, 1999| title=Elon Ganor Named CEO of VocalTec; Company Chairman And Industry Visionary Assumes Leadership.|url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Elon+Ganor+Named+CEO+of+VocalTec%3B+Company+Chairman+And+Industry...-a057427581 |website=thefreelibrary.com}}</ref><ref name="Elon-Ganor-VocalTec">{{cite web| last= Lifschitz| first = Ronny | date =December 15, 99| title= Elon Ganor - VocalTec | url = http://www.globes.co.il/serveen/globes/docview.asp?did=380614| website =http://www.globes.co.il/serveen/globes/nodeview.asp?fid=942}}</ref>
==Biography==
===Early life and career=== Elon Ganor was born in Geneva Switzerland in 1964, grew up in Tel Aviv, Israel where he graduated from [[Tel Aviv University]] Sackler Medical school and got an MD in 1975.
===Entrepreneurship career=== After years of practicing medicine Ganor shifted his energy to the creation of technology related companies. His first company was Virovahl S,A- a Swiss-based biotechnology company that he founded in 1987 with a group of Swedish Virologists, the company's laboratory was located in Gothenburg, Sweden. Virovahl SA, developed the world's first HIV synthetic peptide based on diagnostic test.<ref>{{cite web| date = September 28, 1988| title= Synthetic peptide antigens for the detection of HIV-1 infection. | url = http://www.freepatentsonline.com/EP0284587.html| website = http://www.freepatentsonline.com/}}</ref> Under his guidance as President of Virovahl, the test was licensed exclusively to [[Pharmacia]] AB from Uppsala Sweden (Later merged with [[Upjohn]]).<ref name="Elon-Ganor-VocalTec"/>
In 1990 Ganor joined forces with [[Alon Cohen]] and [[Lior Haramaty]] who formed 6 months earlier VocalTec LTd in Israel. Cohen and Haramaty developed and manufactured a PC sound card (SpeechBoard TM) that was sold mainly to the local visually impaired community in Israel with a unique Text to Speech software enabling blind people to use a computer in the Hebrew language. Since that market was limited, as VocalTec CEO and Chairman, Ganor decided to shift the company's focus to software. In 1993 VocalChat was born, a software that enabled voice communication from one PC to another on a local and wide area network.<ref>{{cite web| date = February 14, 94| title= VOCALTEC INTRODUCES VOCALCHAT WAN FOR VOICE COMMUNICATIONS OVER CORPORATE WIDE AREA NETWORKS. | url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/VOCALTEC+INTRODUCES+VOCALCHAT+WAN+FOR+VOICE+COMMUNICATIONS+OVER...-a014804936| website = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/}}</ref> The software was developed by a group of developers including Ofer Kahana (later the founder of Kagoor that was sold to Juniper),<ref>{{cite web| date = March 29, 2005| title= JUNIPER NETWORKS, INC. TO ACQUIRE KAGOOR NETWORKS. | url = http://www.juniper.net/us/en/company/press-center/press-releases/2005/kgr/pr-050329.html| website = http://www.juniper.net/us/en/}}</ref> Elad Sion (Served in Israel TOP 8200 Intelligence army unit, died young in a car accident), Ofer Shem Tov (A software developer in Israel)<ref name="von" /> and others. The software was presented in Atlanta in May 1993 at the Network InterOp trade show.<ref name="von" /> In 1994 support for Internet Protocol was added and on Friday, February 10, 1995 “Internet Phone“ was launched with a near full page Wall Street Journal article by WSJ Boston Correspondent Bill Bulkeley, “Hello World! Audible chats On the Internet” was the header.<ref name ="wallstreetjournal" />
VocalTec Ltd became a Nasdaq traded company exactly one year later in February 1996 with Ganor as its Chairman & CEO. In 1997 Ganor with the help of Michael Spencer (At the time Principal at [[Booz Allen Hamilton]] who led the Internet Strategy Group of the Communications, Media and Technology practice) wrote the business plan for a new type of a VoIP exchange phone company.<ref name="von" /> After meeting [[Tom Evslin]] from [[AT&T]] (who led at the time WorldNet AT&T ISP initiative) [[ITXC]] was founded, With Tom Evslin as its CEO and cofounder.<ref>{{cite web |title=VoIP Nostalgia |url=http://blog.tomevslin.com/2007/10/voip-nostalgia.html |website=http://blog.tomevslin.com/ }}</ref> VocalTec under Ganor invested the initial $500K and gave a credit of $1Million in VoIP Gateway equipment in exchange of 19.9% of the new company, AT&T followed with an additional investment.<ref>{{cite web| date = August 18, 99 | title= "Maariv": ITXC, in Which VocalTec Holds 19.9%, to Be Issued at $300 Mln Value|url =http://www.globes.co.il/serveen/globes/docview.asp?did=377421|website =http://www.globes.co.il/serveen/globes/nodeview.asp?fid=942}}</ref> ITXC became the world's largest VoIP Carrier reaching a market cap of about $8 Billion as a Nasdaq company in 2000 (prior to the March 2008 crash).{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}
In 2008 Ganor became the founder, investor and CEO (with Danny Frumkin, PhD and Adam Wasserstrom, PhD as co-founders) of Nucleix. Nucleix Ltd is a [[Biotechnology]] epigenetic company involved in unique development of Bio-Markers and technologies for Forensic medicine. The company developed a product for the authentication of DNA.<ref>{{cite web| date = August 20, 2009 |last=Blankenhorn|first=Dana | title= Former VocalTec CEO takes on biological identity theft|url =http://www.smartplanet.com/blog/thinking-tech/former-vocaltec-ceo-takes-on-biological-identity-theft/1140|website =http://www.smartplanet.com/}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news| date= August 17, 2009|last=Pollack|first=Andrew|title= DNA Evidence Can Be Fabricated, Scientists Show|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/18/science/18dna.html?_r=0%7C|work=The New York Times}}</ref> <ref name="cnn" /><ref>{{cite journal |last=Frumkin |first=D |last2=Wasserstrom |first2=A|last3=Davidson |first3=A |last4=Grafit|first4=A|date=February 4, 2010 |title=Authentication of forensic DNA samples |journal=Forensic Science International: Genetics|issue=2 |pages=95–103 |doi=10.1016/j.fsigen.2009.06.009 |pmid=20129467 |volume=4}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|date=August 18, 2009|title= Israeli Scientists Prove DNA Evidence Can Be Faked|last= Levi Julian|first=Hana|url= http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/132965#.UoUuC9-SbSw|website= http://www.israelnationalnews.com}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|date=August 17, 2009|title=Nucleix Researchers Discover DNA Evidence May Easily Be Falsified |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2009/08/17/idUS118263+17-Aug-2009+PRN20090817|website=https://www.reuters.com/}}</ref>
===Art career=== Ganor left VocalTec in 2006 to enroll back to school to study art at Midrasha Leomanut Beit Berl, Israel. Graduated in 2008 with Photography being his main passion and focus.<ref>{{cite news |last=Alon |first=Ktzia |date=September 14, 2008 |title=שואו ביזנס: מיני-אינדקס של "הקפיטליזם בתמונות" למתחילים |trans-title=Show biz: mini-index of "Capitalism in pictures" for beginners|url=http://www.globes.co.il/news/article.aspx?did=1000381668 |language=Hebrew |newspaper=Globes}}</ref> Among his works, “Wall Street” a series of staged photographs shot in NY and Israel expressing criticism of Wall Street practices (first exhibited in 2008 just before the [[Lehman Bros]] collapse). Also among other series, “The Box” (exhibited in 2009 at Volta show in Switzerland)<ref>{{cite web |title=Volta10|url=http://voltashow.com/Elon-Ganor.5701.0.html }}</ref> and Earl King (exhibited in October 2010). Ganor’s art is present in many art collections including the Tel Aviv Museum of Art,<ref name="p8gallery">{{cite web |title=Elon Ganor|url=http://www.p8gallery.net/#!elon-ganor/c17bm }}</ref> Shpilman institute Photography collection,{{citation needed|date=November 2013}} was presented by the [[Israel Museum]] in Jerusalem and many private collections.<ref name="p8gallery" />
