{{Infobox Person | name = Souad Al-Humaidhi | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | native_name = سعاد حمد الصالح الحميضي | native_name_lang = ar |honorific_suffix=[[National Order of the Cedar|NOC]] | birth_place = [[Kuwait City]], Kuwait |birth_date=1939 | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|2017|8|3|1939}} | death_place = Kuwait | death_cause = | residence = | other_names = | spouse =Sheik Jaber Al Ali Al-Salem Al-Sabah | partner = | occupation =Businesswoman | employer = | children = | parents =Suad Hamad Saled Al Homaizi <small>(father)</small> | nationality = }}
'''Sheika Souad Al-Humaidhi''' (1939 &ndash; 3 August 2017) was Kuwaiti businesswoman, owner of a range of commercial and residential complexes in and outside Kuwait, among them and a residential hotel and a tower in [[Beirut]]. Is also member of the Union of Real Estate Owners in Kuwait, of the Board of Directors of [[Bank Audi]] in Lebanon and holds stakes in several banks throughout Kuwait, including the [[National Bank of Kuwait]] and [[Solidere]].<ref>[https://www.arabianbusiness.com/rich-list-2009/list?itemid=150328 27 Suad Al Humaidi]</ref><ref>[https://www.arabianbusiness.com/100-most-powerful-arab-women-2011-384182.html?itemid=383766 8 Suad Al Humaidi]</ref><ref>[https://www.arabianbusiness.com/the-world-s-100-most-powerful-arab-women-541034.html?itemid=540920 46 Suad Al Humaidi]</ref>
== Biography == Souad Al-Humaidhi was the first Kuwaiti woman to practice trade and investment in the country and in several Arab and European countries. She was also one of the most prominent investors in the field of real estate, in the banking and industry and others.<ref>[http://news.kuwaittimes.net/website/amiri-diwan-mourns-suad-al-humaidhi/ Amiri Diwan mourns Suad Al-Humaidhi]</ref>
She worked at the beginning of her career at [[Commercial Bank of Kuwait|Commercial Bank]], founded by her father, Hamad Al-Humaidhi, for 10 years. And then headed the management of her father's institution, trade and investments after his death: "Suad Hamad Saled Al Homaizi Establishment"<ref>[https://marcopolis.net/sheikha-suad-al-humaidhi.htm Sheikha Suad Al Humaidhi]</ref>. At that stage, her husband Sheikh Jaber Al-Ali Al-Salem Al-Sabah, former Minister of Information, supported and encouraged her. He described her as having the wisdom and the comprehensive knowledge of the various issues."<ref>[http://www.nationalkuwait.com/forum/index.php?threads/2708/ سعاد الحميضي في مشوار العمر: أحب الأناقة منذ طفولتيي .. وجلسات الضحى لا تجذبني] {{ar icon}}</ref>
Souad Al-Humaidhi's career in the private sector was not easy, especially in the beginning because she was the first Kuwaiti woman to do business. She says she has faced many difficulties and challenges, including, for example, the Kuwaiti society's view at the time of women's work. But overcame it with self-confidence, self-respect and dedication to work. Success has been its ally in the business, expanding its investments and diversifying and spreading from Kuwait to many Arab countries, especially Lebanon. [[Rafic Hariri]] respected her because she adheres to honesty in treatment. She also built mosques and helped those in need.<ref>[https://alqabas.com/422607/ الكويت تفقد سعاد الحميضي] {{ar icon}}</ref><ref>[https://www.wealthx.com/dossier/suad-hamad-saleh-al-homaizi/ Suad Hamad Saleh Al Homaizi]</ref> She died on 3 August 2017 at the age of 78. == Positions == *Member of the Board of Directors of Bank Audi. *Member of the Board of Directors of Commercial Bank of Kuwait. *Founding member of Ahli Bank of Kuwait. *Chairman of Hamad Al Saleh Al Humaidhi Trading & Contracting. *Chairman of Soad Al Humaidhi General Trading & Contracting. *Chairman of the Board of Directors of the grandchildren of Hamad Saleh for General Trading and Contracting. *Member of the Board of Directors of Al-Abrar Company for General Trading and Contracting. *Founder in the real estate trading company. *Founder of United Real Estate Company. *Founder of Salhia Real Estate Company. *Owned 20% of the Lebanese Bank Audi. *Owned 20% of the Egyptian Company for the manufacture of cans. *Owned 20% of the Pepsi Cola bottling company. *Owned many investments in many Arab countries, especially Kuwait and Lebanon.<ref>[https://www.eremnews.com/economy/937047 وفاة سعاد الحميضي أشهر سيدة أعمال كويتية] {{ar icon}}</ref>
== Awards and achievements == *Rafik Harir awarded her with the [[National Order of the Cedar]].<ref>[https://www.msn.com/ar-sa/news/middleeast/%D8%B3%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B6%D9%8A%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B9%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%8A%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B2%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%B0%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87/ar-AApnlUL?li=BBqrFIf سعاد الحميضي..سيدة الأعمال الكويتية البارزة في ذمة الله] {{ar icon}}</ref> *Contributed to the project of expansion and rehabilitation of the [[Al-Omari Grand Mosque]] in central Beirut.<ref>[https://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=1479551&language=en Grand Mosque of Beirut reopened after restoration]</ref> *Suad Al Humaidhi is ranked 10th in Arabian Business magazine's ranking for the Arab Woman of the Year 2013.<ref>[http://www.sayidaty.net/node/597496/%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AC%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B9/%D8%A3%D8%AE%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1-%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D8%A9-%D9%88%D9%85%D8%AC%D8%AA%D9%85%D8%B9/%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%AF%D8%A9-%D8%B3%D9%8A%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%A3%D8%B9%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%84-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%83%D9%88%D9%8A%D8%AA%D9%8A%D8%A7%D8%AA-%D8%B3%D8%B9%D8%A7%D8%AF-%D8%A7%D9%84%D8%AD%D9%85%D9%8A%D8%B6%D9%8A-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D8%B0%D9%85%D8%A9-%D8%A7%D9%84%D9%84%D9%87#photo/1 رائدة سيدات الأعمال الكويتيات سعاد الحميضي في ذمة الله] {{ar icon}}</ref> *She was also honored by the activities of the Arab Women Forum and the Future held in Dubai in 2007. *The [[Prime Minister of Kuwait|Prime Minister]] [[Jaber Al-Mubarak Al-Hamad Al-Sabah|Sheikh Jaber Al-Mubarak]] honored her with a certificate of thanks for her participation in the film «Climate Crisis and the reality of what happened». *She was honored by the wife of former [[Hosni Mubarak|Egyptian President]] [[Suzanne Mubarak]] at a meeting of the Arab Businesswomen's Council.
